,Recommended,227580,925537,"Posted: 22 January, 2013",all,7grain,"I thoroughly enjoyed this fine little time waster.So, yes. It's kind of like Bejeweled. The matches you make down below push your character through combat and exploration above. Each ""run"" through the dungeon takes a minute or two. But as you run, you achieve a series of objectives which the game gradually presents to you, which leads to improved skills.The game's genius is the way it rewards you not for a lifetime score, but instead for pushing your single-run high score higher and higher, until you can reach 10,000,000 in a single run. As your character improves a bit with each run, cresting your previous high score becomes theoretically easier each time you run the dungeon. Die, and you can either quit the game, or try one more run almost instantly.It's not a deep game, but I can't think of many games that made ""just one more turn"" so compelling. Like, ""Civilization""-style compelling. It's so easy to try again, over and over. A minute here, a minute there, next thing you know, 2 hours have gone by."
76561198035808481,Recommended,227580,34835427,Posted: 9 September,all,krozzus,"Ten Million is a nice little match 3 puzzlegame in which the end goal is to score ten million points.Your run ends when you run out of time, with your character slowly moving towards the left of the screen as time goes on with the left edge being the end of you. Taking damage through enemies pushes you even further quickly, getting kills among other things pushes you to the right again.You play by dragging a line or column around and then having at least 3 of the same tile in a line. There is only a few tiles that dont change either and each has its own use, swords and staffs do physical and magical attacks, keys unlock doors and chests etc. Above the field you can see what you are currently faced with and therefor know if you for example need to match key tiles.During each run you gain ressources that all serve the purpose to make you stronger and go further, be it by having your attack tiles do more damage or by increasing your defense or increasing critical hit chance etc. While this means you grind for ressources run for run it doesnt really feel like a grind upgrading is more like something on the side to do next to playing the game.Another distraction is the little side quests that you get, many are luck based or happen sooner or later anyway, like matching 5 of the same tile in a single strike multiple times in one run, others require you to use specific items (that you randomly acquire during runs and since you can only carry 3/4  use quickly again anyway)While you will gain ressources no matter how you play the game does reward you for playing well, for example if you manage to be so far ahead of time that you end up on the right edge of the screen and can keep that up for a bit it gives you a nice amount of bonus experience or gold and big chain reactions or 5 tiles in a row etc also benefit you.In the end getting to the 10000000 scorepoint isnt that complicated, especially if you have every single upgrade and think carefully what potions to use, however the steam achievements crank it up a notch requiring you to achieve that same score with a much lower point multiplier, setting an endgoal even people who are good at these games will have to work for to reach.You can probably beat the game in less than 4 hours though i would say it isnt really made to rush through in one sitting, rather to unwind with a little puzzlegame for a bit every evening, or something like that. And while the pricepoint is higher than many similar games I would say it is almost worth it and totally worth it when on sale for even less."
