,Recommended,227580,10202051,"Posted: 22 May, 2014",all,RANVEERA CHINGAAH,"Match-3 meets procedurally generated, forbiddingly difficult dungeon delving.If you like spending hours matching 3 while bobbing your head to a kickin' tune, you will probably enjoy the core mechanic that this game gets you to grind for a good handful of hours to get all its unlockables and have a good chance of actually achieving the objective.There's a lot of character here, from your little faceless protagonist's enthusiasm when he flip-jumps out of bed every morning to go dungeoneering to the array of monsters you face, although I have to admit I was slightly happier with them when I thought the ""goblin cannon squad"" was actually a diseased cat coughing some kind of deadly hairball at me.You won't spend long with this game, but what time you spend will be spent doing more or less the same thing. Don't buy it if you don't already like match-3 puzzlers at least a little bit.You will definitely be frustrated by bad luck when you just can't get enough swords, keys, or staves at the right moments, or realize you were desperately looking for a match when you could have just used the handy standby you had in your pocket and forgot about. However, if you're up for a little frustration in the search of fun and you like puzzles and old-fashioned Nethack-style dungeons, this is the game for you. I bought it at full price and had a lot of fun with it. It was a little like Super Hexagon in its ability to keep me playing for hours just trying to get that one run that does well enough.If you're still not sure, go check out a YouTube video for some game footage. There's no plot to spoil, so you can still enjoy the game for yourself after watching someone else play it a bit, and that will probably tell you whether you want to try it or not."
